Effect of recent divergence - dispersal

Larval type Planktotrophic/pelagic larvae leads to less CS/NS)?

Note1: for this Im working with a separate surveylarv input file where I have corrected larval types to pt, lt, dd, and removed all others, including cases where there are multiple types checked. (Most of those cases are where the two CS have different larvae.) This left 107 CS with larval info.

Note2: the data fail the homoscedasticity test (Bartletts) so Ive used a nonparametric Kruskal-Wallis test to see if CS/NS is different among groups.

##       DD       PT 
## 3.622642 2.777778
##       DD       PT 
## 2.363394 1.253925
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  as.numeric(larv_NbCS$Nb_CS) and larv_NbCS$Larv_type
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 3.4091, df = 1, p-value = 0.06484

Hypothesis marginally supported. DD with higher CS per NS.

High HKK leads to more CS ss testing this based on Nb_CS per HKK.

Note: data again failed homoscedasticity, using Kruskal Wallis test

##        5       10       25      100     1000 
## 3.437500 3.750000 2.387097 3.615385 3.400000
##        5       10       25      100     1000 
## 2.031010 3.046608 0.843699 1.709701 2.698659
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  HKK_NbCS$Nb_CS and HKK_NbCS$HKKv3
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 11.177, df = 4, p-value = 0.02465

Result: Hypothesis only marginally supported. There are differences here but no clear trend - HKK=25 is clearly lowest and then higher on both ends.

In sum, some support for the role of recent divergence as measured by a proxy of dispersal when considering only the arthropods.

Stabilizing selection

More stable environments = more CSss or statistical differences

Note: stable = pelagic, deepsea, cave, coralreef; not stable = coastal, intertidal, estuarine, seagrass

##        
##         FALSE TRUE
##   FALSE    33    9
##   TRUE     34   30
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  stable_hab$CSss and stable_hab$Stable
## X-squared = 6.0089, df = 1, p-value = 0.01423
##                FALSE      TRUE
## CSss_total 0.5074627 0.7692308
## CSsl_total 0.4925373 0.2307692

Result: More CSss found in stable environments. Hypothesis supported.

Note also that stabilizing selection predicts more CSss than CSsl, which is not what we find (see above).

In sum, we generally have support for this idea.

High Ne (neutral hypotheses)

Reproductive investment - Low reproductive investment leads to more statistical divergence? (Repro. investment proxy for Ne)

Note1: Again this uses the surveylarv dataset with hand cleaning. Note2: Planktotrophic = LOW; Lecithotrophic, Brooding, DD = HIGH; If a spp could be both low and high, have marked it NA (is usually bc the CS have different larval types). Anything else got marked NA to be conservative. Note3: Only 61 cases are considered here, meaning that is where we have morphological data AND larval type data AND Arthropod
